                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> I find your presumptions to be flawed.  I'd like to tackle a few of them.<br /><br />First, 'It's a game'.  Everquest is not 'just' a game.  My guildleader used what I found to be an apt example:  Log on to any other server with a level 1 character where you know no-one.  Run around killing newb-zone trash. That's a game.  Now log into your primary character surrounded by your guildmates and spend your evening with them as a team, taking on mobs and amassing loot that without a group effort nobody would ever see.  That's a community.  If I want to play a game, I'll pop Zelda into my Gamecube, or play Splinter Cell on my XBox.  Everquest is a community I choose to involve myself with, and the friends I have there are as dear to me as any others I have in life.  We meet, we socialize, we make cross-country trips to visit each other and we all get together yearly.  If that's a 'game', then life itself is a game.<br /><br />Now, as far as the game elements go, 'fun' is not the only goal.  Hell, 'fun' for me would be to pay 12 bucks a month to have all the gear that a typical Fires of Heaven necro would have.  Shouldn't Sony provide that for me?  No.  Sony must balance things as best they can, and from the perspective of over a dozen different classes, having only a quarter of those able to solo is a bit unbalanced in some people's viewpoints.  Having one specific group able to outstrip every other group in the game at a signifigant element of that game is unbalanced.<br /><br />So up the bar for everyone!  I tend to agree to a point.  In my opinion, the ******** one must put up with to form and maintain a group should merit MORE rewards for a group than they ever would solo.  Soloing should always be an option.  Soloing should never be the most lucrative option.<br /><br />You have to set an arbitrary carrot, as well.  Things can't be too easy.  What will Joe Necro with 400+ AA's do now for fun?  The ease of the game cannot outstrip the ability of the designers to come up with new carrots.<br /><br />Necros were quite upset for a long time that they had very little to bring to raids.  They didn't stack.  Many guilds saw them as mana *****s and nothing more.  Verant has gone some distance toward mitigating that lack (Though I think they could do more in that direction), but if you flip the coin, isn't there just as serious a problem with the raid classes not being able to effectively XP without being shackled to a group structure?<br /><br />The 'nerf' was needed.  I think it was particularly harsh for necromancers bacause of the limited and dangerous situations that a necro could use his charm.  They didn't go far enough with Enchanters and Druids, however.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
