                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> If the game ended today, I'd most likely take the friends that I've made to some other game.  Worlds of Warcraft, perhaps (When it comes out).  My point is that a game is something I sit down at and play for a few hours.  Halo is a game.  When I schedule parts of my life around a game, it's no longer 'just a game'.  It's 'Tonight is X person's quest mob' or 'Tonight the guys need me in Vex Thal'.  Sure, it's a game, in the sense that a community league is a game.  If I sign up to play softball, I have a responsibility to the team to practice, show up, et cetera. Things that affect that game affect my life and my friends.  That may be difficult to sell to the stereotypical necromancer, but I started as a cleric.  I'm ingrained to rely on others as they rely on me.<br /><br />How is Everquest any less 'a life' than going to bars after work and hanging out with a crew there?  How is Everquest less a life than going fishing?  I think bowling is pretty stupid, myself, but I don't denigrate the bowler for his obsession.<br /><br />Then again, very few bowlers spend 30+ hours a week at the lanes.<br /><br />Still, you can trivialize Everquest as a 'game' all you want, but the truth is that people treat it as more than a game.  That's not going to stop by saying 'get a life'.<br /><br />It's all off the subject, however.  The initial premise was that this is a GAME and should be FUN and therefore Sony should be more interested in giving us candy than in taking away our toys.  I disagree.<br /><br />And why shouldn't all classes be subjectively equivalent?  Why should my cleric have so few resources for soloing when he can't find a group?  Why should a necromancer be unable to stack his damage on a raid when melee classes and nuke classes can?  Balance is subjective, and charm was ****ing broken.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
